\section{ Potentiometer as a voltage divider}
\index{Experiment: Potentiometer as voltage divider}
 

\textbf{PARTS AND MATERIALS}
 

\begin{itemize}
\item Two 6-volt batteries
\item Carbon pencil "lead" for a mechanical-style pencil
\item Potentiometer, single turn, 5 k$\Omega$ to 50 k$\Omega$, linear taper (Radio Shack catalog \# 271-1714 through 271-1716)
\item Potentiometer, multi turn, 1 k$\Omega$ to 20 k$\Omega$, (Radio Shack catalog \# 271-342, 271-343, 900-8583, or 900-8587 through 900-8590)
\end{itemize}
\index{Potentiometer}
 

Potentiometers are variable voltage dividers with a shaft or slide control for setting the division ratio.  They are manufactured in panel-mount as well as breadboard (printed-circuit board) mount versions.  Any style of potentiometer will suffice for this experiment.
 

\index{Potentiometer, linear vs. audio taper}
\index{Audio taper potentiometer}
\index{Linear taper potentiometer}
 

If you salvage a potentiometer from an old radio or other audio device, you will likely be getting what is called an \textit{audio taper} potentiometer.  These potentiometers exhibit a logarithmic relationship between division ratio and shaft position.  By contrast, a \textit{linear} potentiometer exhibits a direct correlation between shaft position and voltage division ratio.  I highly recommend a linear potentiometer for this experiment, and for most experiments in general.
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{CROSS-REFERENCES}
 

 

\textit{Lessons In Electric Circuits}, Volume 1, chapter 6: "Divider Circuits and Kirchhoff's Laws"
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{LEARNING OBJECTIVES}
 

\begin{itemize}
\item Voltmeter use
\item Ohmmeter use
\item Voltage divider design and function
\item How voltages add in series
\end{itemize}
\bigskip 
 

\textbf{SCHEMATIC DIAGRAM}
 

 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{05106.eps}} 
\bigskip 
 

\textbf{ILLUSTRATION}
 

 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{05107.eps}} 
 

 

\bigskip 
 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{05108.eps}} 
 

 

\bigskip 
 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{05109.eps}} 
